Some hoodlums have disrupted the collection of the Permanent Voters Cards (PVCs) in some parts of Ikpoba Okha Local Government Area of Edo State. It was learnt that the incident happened on Friday and Saturday in Ward 01 at Iwogban/Uteh Ward 05 at St. Saviour’s School, Ward 07 at Ugbekun, Ward 06 at Maria Goretti College, RA 09 at Obanyator with Army Children’s School and Ogheghe health centres. The hoodlums were said to have stormed the collection centres in the morning when officials of the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) moved the distribution of the PVC to the ward level. The Head of Voter Education, Edo INEC office, Timidi Wariowe, who reacted in a statement said the disruption happened in five wards of the local government. “The INEC Edo State has received reports of unruly incidents between yesterday, Friday and Saturday which degenerated into the disruption of the collection of PVC and threat to officials and materials in the five wards. “In the meantime, INEC Edo State has decided to move the collection centres for Ward 1 and Ward 9 to the INEC Local Government Office in Ikpoba Okha, while the staff earlier withdrawn from Ward 5, Ward 6 and Ward 7 are making their ways back to their collection centres to continue with the activity, on the assurances that the Electoral Officer has received from the DSS of their presence in those locations”. He said INEC had equally informed the state police command about the situation. He called on the citizens, especially community leaders, on the need to ensure the safety of INEC officials and materials deployed in their various communities to ensure that all voters collects their PVCs and are able to vote in the election. He disclosed that a total of 26,095 PVCs had been collected between the January and 7, ahead of the 2023 general elections.